  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Eight Masters' Poetry Selection
  author: Lee Gae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since the classical and ceremonial odes of antiquity, the authentic voice of poetry has grown ever fainter. Through the Qi and Liang dynasties, countless voices chirped in discord, until the Tang emerged bearing the lingering resonance of the three hundred poems. The great masters celebrated in Song times were but pale echoes of Tang brilliance. Thus those who discourse on poetry speak only of Tang and Song. Yet their collected works sprawl vast and boundless—a curse upon any reader hoping to comprehend them wholly.

    One day, when the Master of Unwearied Diligence broached this very concern, the desire arose to gather and arrange these works into a single volume. Together with two or three fellow scholars, we divided the labor of selection, though he remained the true arbiter. From Tang we chose Li Bai, Du Fu, Wei Yingwu, and Liu Zongyuan; from Song, Ouyang Xiu, Wang Anshi, Huang Tingjian, and Su Shi. We culled their five-character and seven-character regulated verses, their seven-character quatrains—all pieces worthy of emulation—numbering several hundred in total, arranged across ten fascicles for ready perusal.

    Other celebrated masters abound, it is true. Yet to include them all would breed nothing but chaos and confusion. Thus we determined upon these eight, excluding all others. This volume is concise yet refined, elegant yet resplendent—truly a wing to bear aloft the three hundred poems, destined to revive the poetic way and restore the authority of classical song. Its gift to future scholars shall be immeasurable.

    O Master of Unwearied Diligence! Though possessed of keen brilliance and seated in wealth and station, you guard your simplicity with care and find your joy in letters. Your devotion reaches to this sublime height. Even a thousand years hence, through this very collection, posterity shall recognize and cherish your cultivated refinement.
  footnotes:
    - The 'three hundred poems' refers to the Shijing (Book of Poetry), the foundational classical collection.
    - Li Bai (701-762) and Du Fu (712-770) are considered the greatest poets of the Tang dynasty.
    - Wei Yingwu (737-792) and Liu Zongyuan (773-819) were distinguished Tang poets known for their regulated verse.
    - The four Song masters—Ouyang Xiu (1007-1072), Wang Anshi (1021-1086), Su Shi (1037-1101), and Huang Tingjian (1045-1105)—represent the heights of Song poetry.
    - The 'Master of Unwearied Diligence' (匪懈堂) is the personal name or title of the editor who conceived this anthology.
